/KA4. KEDUSHAT HAYOM / THE DAYòS HOLINESS/XX/PR

Happy are we,/PR

how fortunate our lot,/PR

how pleasing is our destiny,/PR

how lovely our inheritance!/PR

Happy are we/PR

to be at rest upon the seventh day,/PR

and thus is written in your Torah:/PR

/PR

Let Israelòs descendants keep Shabbat,/PR

enacting the Shabbat throughout their generations/PR

as an everlasting covenant./PR

Between me and everyone of Israel/PR

shall it be a sign eternally,/PR

for in six days did /SCT/XXHE /XXC/XXREATOR/XX/PR

make the heavens and the earth,/PR

and on the seventh day God ceased,/PR

and drew a breath of rest./PI/PR

/SCC/XXOMMENTARY/XX. /ITKedushat Hayom/XX in Shabbat /ITShah/±arit/XX traditionally begins
with /ITYismah/± Moshe/XX, a paragraph describing Moses with head a glow bring-
ing the Ten Commandments down from Mt. Sinai. It is omitted here
because the sharpness of the imagery suggests a literal belief in the Sinai
event rather than an affirmation of its mythic truth. In its place
"/ITAshreynu/XX / Happy are we" evokes the special nature of the joyous Jewish
heritage of which Shabbat is so integral a part.    /SC/XXD.A.T./XX/PR

/PR

/SCK/XXAVANAH/XX. Consider your own creative power. Think about the work you
have done in the week that has passed, and feel your own pride and pleas-
ure in that work. Then, try to set your work aside. Try not to think about
the work ahead next week. Rather, take a few long, deep breaths, slow
down, and enjoy the chance for rest that Shabbat brings.    /SC/XXL.B./XX/PR

